WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:12.000
Hi, I'm Michael Wascomb. I'm an ML engineer at Flatiron Health, which is a company in

00:00:12.000 --> 00:00:17.600
New York City that uses technology to accelerate cancer research and improve cancer care. But

00:00:17.600 --> 00:00:22.760
I'm here today to talk about Seaborn, a Python library that I'm the creator and maintainer

00:00:22.760 --> 00:00:23.760
of.

00:00:24.760 --> 00:00:30.120
So if you're not familiar, Seaborn is a Python data visualization library that's based on

00:00:30.120 --> 00:00:37.200
the Matplotlib framework. So Matplotlib, very general library, but relatively low-level.

00:00:37.200 --> 00:00:42.880
Seaborn offers a higher-level interface that is specifically geared towards creating statistical

00:00:42.880 --> 00:00:45.880
graphics.

00:00:45.880 --> 00:00:51.480
This talk is going to be about what I've learned over the past decade or so of Seaborn development

00:00:51.959 --> 00:00:59.160
and how that's informed the current and future directions of the library.

00:00:59.160 --> 00:01:04.739
Seaborn started out with pretty humble ambitions. It was essentially a toolbox or an extension

00:01:04.739 --> 00:01:10.480
to Matplotlib that offered a few plotting functions with statistical capabilities, doing

00:01:10.480 --> 00:01:15.879
things like fitting a kernel density estimate to a histogram or a linear regression line

00:01:15.879 --> 00:01:18.239
to a scatter plot.

00:01:18.239 --> 00:01:22.320
And these functions behaved a lot like the rest of Matplotlib. They primarily operated

00:01:22.320 --> 00:01:28.480
on NumPy arrays, because that was the main data structure at the time.

00:01:28.480 --> 00:01:33.599
But this was around when pandas was starting to get popular and bringing the idea of a

00:01:33.599 --> 00:01:37.919
labeled columnar data structure to Python.

00:01:37.919 --> 00:01:43.360
And so some of the early Seaborn functions built on that and borrowed some ideas from

00:01:43.360 --> 00:01:50.239
the R community about tidy data, using data frames at first really to make faceted or

00:01:50.239 --> 00:01:55.599
paired small multiple plots with features like conditional color mapping, where the

00:01:55.599 --> 00:02:04.040
color mapping was really thought of as a faceting operation on the third dimension of the plot.

00:02:04.040 --> 00:02:08.839
And as Seaborn developed, I was primarily concerned with filling gaps in Matplotlib's

00:02:08.839 --> 00:02:15.960
feature set, especially features that were important for emerging data science applications.

00:02:15.960 --> 00:02:20.919
So Matplotlib's roots are in the physical sciences, and it hasn't always served analytics

00:02:20.919 --> 00:02:24.839
and machine learning use cases as well as it could.

00:02:24.839 --> 00:02:31.199
So for instance, one of the first major distinguishing features of Seaborn was its support for categorical

00:02:31.199 --> 00:02:36.880
data and kind of plots that are optimized for categorical data.

00:02:36.880 --> 00:02:42.039
And eventually, this landed us in a kind of odd situation where Seaborn had support

00:02:42.039 --> 00:02:47.759
for some fairly complex graphics, things like regression or violin plots, but not simple

00:02:47.759 --> 00:02:51.880
ones, like just basic line or scatter plots.

00:02:51.880 --> 00:02:57.919
And remember, the initial intention or thought was add on to what Matplotlib doesn't have,

00:02:57.919 --> 00:03:01.520
and Matplotlib already had those things.

00:03:01.520 --> 00:03:05.679
But it didn't have this tidy API, API where you could just pass in a data frame and name

00:03:05.679 --> 00:03:10.160
some columns and have those automatically mapped to components of the plot.

00:03:10.160 --> 00:03:15.839
So almost, I think, five years or so after the first release of Seaborn, it kind of finally

00:03:15.839 --> 00:03:21.000
gained such basics as a line plot and a scatter plot function.

00:03:21.000 --> 00:03:25.899
But not just in their simplest forms, in forms that had support for mapping now up to three

00:03:25.899 --> 00:03:31.160
additional dimensions based on the columns in a data frame, including color and size

00:03:31.160 --> 00:03:36.360
and the style of the elements in the plot.

00:03:36.360 --> 00:03:42.279
And so Seaborn's objective remained help people make plots faster so that they can understand

00:03:42.279 --> 00:03:49.240
their data better, but its focus and how it did that shifted from do their statistics

00:03:49.240 --> 00:03:56.839
for them to give them an intuitive interface that lets them rapidly iterate and think about

00:03:56.839 --> 00:04:01.440
their data, not the mechanics of specifying a graphic.

00:04:01.440 --> 00:04:06.479
And so that prompted me to revisit even some of the oldest functions in the library and

00:04:06.479 --> 00:04:12.639
to try to impose some API consistency onto these tools that had grown rather organically

00:04:12.639 --> 00:04:19.320
and at the start without much intentional thought about API design.

00:04:19.320 --> 00:04:24.579
So despite this somewhat haphazard and organic development, the result, the kind of status

00:04:24.579 --> 00:04:30.779
quo is a library that can be used to produce a relatively wide range of informative statistical

00:04:30.779 --> 00:04:36.299
graphics with a reasonably coherent API.

00:04:36.299 --> 00:04:43.779
And the API model, the API encourages a mental model where you might say, I want to make

00:04:43.779 --> 00:04:48.059
a line plot, and then there's a function called line plot that you can do to do that.

00:04:48.059 --> 00:04:52.980
Or there's a function called bar plot, and you can probably guess what that does.

00:04:52.980 --> 00:04:56.299
So one objective of Seaborn is that each of these functions should be able to produce

00:04:56.299 --> 00:05:02.940
a usable plot with a bare minimum set of arguments, really just enough to specify the data.

00:05:02.940 --> 00:05:07.820
They make some inferences about what you want based on the data types, and they try to use

00:05:07.820 --> 00:05:11.100
sensible defaults, and they produce complete graphics.

00:05:11.100 --> 00:05:15.500
They add labels and legends, so you can very quickly get from an idea or a question you

00:05:15.500 --> 00:05:19.339
have to a plot that you could at least show to one of your colleagues, and they'd understand

00:05:19.339 --> 00:05:22.420
what it is.

00:05:22.420 --> 00:05:25.059
But customization is important.

00:05:25.059 --> 00:05:28.739
Good customization requires rapid iteration.

00:05:28.739 --> 00:05:34.459
And so each function exposes a number of additional parameters that afford varying kinds of control.

00:05:34.459 --> 00:05:39.980
So these range from specifying the mappings between your dataset to the visual properties

00:05:39.980 --> 00:05:44.880
in the plot, setting hyperparameters of whatever statistical operations that function's going

00:05:44.880 --> 00:05:48.500
to perform, and tweaking the plot's final appearance.

00:05:49.500 --> 00:05:54.339
Now, it's not quite true that you can customize everything just through the parameters of

00:05:54.339 --> 00:05:56.019
the Seaborn functions.

00:05:56.019 --> 00:06:01.339
Recall that it started with the idea of, you know, like Matplotlib, but with some statistics,

00:06:01.339 --> 00:06:06.420
and so the functions were meant to fit into the standard Matplotlib workflow, which means

00:06:06.420 --> 00:06:11.899
that while Seaborn will add default labels to the plot, if you want to customize them,

00:06:11.899 --> 00:06:14.779
you'd use Matplotlib's API for that.

00:06:15.779 --> 00:06:20.220
Still, you can get most of the way there by interacting just with the Seaborn API, and

00:06:20.220 --> 00:06:24.420
that's helped, you know, a lot of people make a lot of useful plots.

00:06:24.420 --> 00:06:27.660
But I've also come to appreciate, you know, over the years, some of the limitations that

00:06:27.660 --> 00:06:29.540
this design imposes.

00:06:32.380 --> 00:06:37.700
So one obvious consequence is that each of these parameters has a, or each of these functions

00:06:37.700 --> 00:06:40.459
has a lot of parameters.

00:06:40.500 --> 00:06:45.579
And any one function's parameters do a lot of different kinds of things.

00:06:45.579 --> 00:06:49.540
So while on the one hand, you know, it's straightforward to explain how Seaborn works.

00:06:49.540 --> 00:06:51.140
You're just specifying parameters.

00:06:51.140 --> 00:06:54.260
You find a function that you think is going to do what you want, you look at its list

00:06:54.260 --> 00:06:57.980
of parameters to see what options it has.

00:06:57.980 --> 00:07:03.299
But with so many parameters, and just in one, you know, linear list, it can be hard to know,

00:07:03.299 --> 00:07:09.739
you know, what bits and pieces you're going to need to solve any specific problem.

00:07:09.739 --> 00:07:14.779
And then because Seaborn is a higher level interface to Matplotlib, some of the parameters

00:07:14.779 --> 00:07:19.380
that you need to set might actually be Matplotlib parameters.

00:07:19.380 --> 00:07:24.299
And even just within Seaborn, some functions are at a higher level than others.

00:07:24.299 --> 00:07:31.220
And so the API relies heavily on keyword argument passing, which means to understand what parameters

00:07:31.220 --> 00:07:36.519
a function takes, you might need to walk through several different pages of documentation across

00:07:36.519 --> 00:07:41.839
multiple project websites.

00:07:41.839 --> 00:07:46.920
And the, you know, organic development of the library has led to an expanding scope

00:07:46.920 --> 00:07:51.359
over time has led to some other opportunities for friction or confusion.

00:07:51.359 --> 00:07:57.480
So take, you know, as a case study, the strip plot and the scatterplot functions.

00:07:57.480 --> 00:08:02.799
These are both fundamentally scatterplots, or what they create are fundamentally scatterplots.

00:08:02.799 --> 00:08:07.559
But as I mentioned earlier, the function called strip plot actually came first, because

00:08:07.559 --> 00:08:10.799
it's a scatterplot that's optimized for categorical data.

00:08:10.799 --> 00:08:15.480
It's meant as an alternative or a complement to a box or violin plot.

00:08:15.480 --> 00:08:23.079
So it has capabilities like dodging and jittering that makes sense in that context.

00:08:23.079 --> 00:08:27.079
And then the scatterplot function came later, producing plots that are in one sense more

00:08:27.079 --> 00:08:33.200
basic, but on the other hand have more options for mapping properties based on data.

00:08:33.200 --> 00:08:36.880
They allow you to control the size of the dots and the shape of the markers, whereas

00:08:36.880 --> 00:08:40.119
strip plot only controls the color.

00:08:40.119 --> 00:08:44.280
So you know, you might find yourself starting to make a plot using one of these functions,

00:08:44.280 --> 00:08:48.460
realizing that it can't do everything you want, switching to one of the other functions,

00:08:48.460 --> 00:08:54.400
and then realizing you've lost some of the features that you were relying on.

00:08:54.400 --> 00:08:59.640
Now you can always add features, but the design makes this hard too.

00:08:59.640 --> 00:09:04.359
And paradoxically, it can feel hardest to add small features, small little nice-to-haves

00:09:04.359 --> 00:09:11.799
that just add a little polish or satisfy a few less common use cases.

00:09:11.799 --> 00:09:17.080
So as an example, take the concept of adding a gap or a little spacing between the boxes

00:09:17.080 --> 00:09:19.159
in a box plot when you dodge them.

00:09:19.159 --> 00:09:24.080
It's a totally reasonable thing, you know, I like the way this looks.

00:09:24.080 --> 00:09:31.320
But implementing it would mean adding a parameter to box plot to control whether there's a gap,

00:09:31.320 --> 00:09:33.320
how big the gap is.

00:09:33.320 --> 00:09:37.520
And so that already long list of parameters is going to grow a little bit, and that's

00:09:37.520 --> 00:09:40.320
going to impose an ongoing cost to usability.

00:09:40.320 --> 00:09:43.280
Everyone in the future who comes and looks at the list of parameters is going to have

00:09:43.280 --> 00:09:49.400
one more that they need to sift through to understand what they can do.

00:09:49.400 --> 00:09:53.140
And here's the thing, despite the way it's articulated on GitHub here, this isn't really

00:09:53.140 --> 00:09:57.419
just a request about the box plot function.

00:09:57.419 --> 00:10:04.099
Adding this would also mean changing the bar plot function and the violin plot function.

00:10:04.099 --> 00:10:10.140
All of the other functions that have some sort of dodging operation, you either have

00:10:10.140 --> 00:10:14.619
to change all of them or you have to add more inconsistency or accept more inconsistency

00:10:14.619 --> 00:10:16.260
in the library.

00:10:16.260 --> 00:10:21.580
And so beyond implementing that operation in the code itself, each function also has

00:10:21.580 --> 00:10:24.140
tests and documentation that would need to be updated.

00:10:24.140 --> 00:10:30.299
So it just increases the costs of adding even small things.

00:10:30.299 --> 00:10:34.419
When Seaborn's functions don't support a feature, one option is to drop down to the underlying

00:10:34.419 --> 00:10:37.500
matplotlib layer or accomplish what you want there.

00:10:37.500 --> 00:10:41.380
Matplotlib's still a Python library, lots of people know how to use it, and this was

00:10:41.380 --> 00:10:42.940
part of the original design, right?

00:10:42.940 --> 00:10:46.380
Seaborn was just adding some things that you couldn't do in matplotlib, so if there was

00:10:46.380 --> 00:10:51.979
something it couldn't do, no harm, you just carry on as if Seaborn wasn't there.

00:10:51.979 --> 00:10:57.159
But as Seaborn has developed more capabilities in its own style of API, the gap between the

00:10:57.159 --> 00:11:02.219
two libraries has grown, and so it's no longer a valid assumption, and it's also no longer

00:11:02.219 --> 00:11:07.859
a valid assumption that any Seaborn user is also comfortable using matplotlib.

00:11:07.859 --> 00:11:11.020
Lots of places have started teaching data science using Seaborn because it's a little

00:11:11.020 --> 00:11:16.780
easier, a little bit faster to get started out of the box.

00:11:16.780 --> 00:11:21.460
So after nearly a decade, I decided to take a step back and think, if I were designing

00:11:21.460 --> 00:11:27.219
this library from scratch and had from the start a focus on a flexible but consistent

00:11:27.219 --> 00:11:32.539
interface that was easy to use and didn't constrain what you could do, what would that

00:11:32.539 --> 00:11:36.859
look like?

00:11:36.859 --> 00:11:42.659
So the result is what I'm calling the Objects Interface, or Seaborn.objects.

00:11:42.659 --> 00:11:47.840
It's a totally new approach, basically a ground-up rewrite that takes inspiration both from things

00:11:47.840 --> 00:11:52.780
that worked well in classic Seaborn and from libraries that are more explicitly based on

00:11:52.780 --> 00:12:00.140
the formal grammar of graphics, like ggplot, also Vega, parts of D3, other libraries that

00:12:00.140 --> 00:12:05.739
are out there that are built on some of these ideas.

00:12:05.739 --> 00:12:10.020
So while people have sometimes referred to classic Seaborn as ggplot in Python, I've

00:12:10.020 --> 00:12:14.059
always thought that's wrong, or at least overselling it.

00:12:14.059 --> 00:12:18.059
Seaborn has certainly taken ideas and inspiration from ggplot since the beginning, but it's

00:12:18.059 --> 00:12:20.280
also always had a narrower ambition.

00:12:20.280 --> 00:12:26.219
It's not intended to be a fully flexible system for producing graphics.

00:12:26.219 --> 00:12:32.159
The Objects Interface is much more explicitly based on the underlying formalism and also

00:12:32.159 --> 00:12:36.119
has somewhat broader ambitions to be more general.

00:12:36.119 --> 00:12:38.159
It's still not ggplot in Python, though.

00:12:38.159 --> 00:12:43.359
It's not going to be a direct port of the syntax that you might be used to if you're

00:12:43.359 --> 00:12:45.299
a ggplot user.

00:12:45.299 --> 00:12:47.280
It should feel familiar, I hope.

00:12:47.280 --> 00:12:53.960
I think the learning curve should be pretty rapid, but it's a different library.

00:12:53.960 --> 00:12:58.039
I always say that if what you want is just to take your ggplot code and have it run in

00:12:58.039 --> 00:13:02.919
Python, you should check out the Plot9 library, and today you're in luck because you just

00:13:02.919 --> 00:13:05.880
have to wait a few minutes and you'll hear about that.

00:13:05.880 --> 00:13:12.320
But for the time being, let me walk you through how I've approached this in Seaborn.

00:13:12.320 --> 00:13:17.320
So everything in the Objects Interface is built around an object called plot.

00:13:17.320 --> 00:13:22.359
Plot has a number of methods, and you call these methods to specify how various aspects

00:13:22.359 --> 00:13:23.679
of the graph should appear.

00:13:23.679 --> 00:13:28.559
So that includes data specification, adding layers, parameterizing the scales, customizing

00:13:28.559 --> 00:13:31.239
the decorations, and the theme of the plot.

00:13:31.239 --> 00:13:37.039
Every time you call one of its methods, you're gradually adding on to the spec.

00:13:37.039 --> 00:13:41.679
And it's called the Objects Interface because beyond plot, there's a number of other objects

00:13:41.679 --> 00:13:46.159
that you pass to plot's methods to define the graph.

00:13:46.159 --> 00:13:53.239
So there's four basic types of objects, mark, stat, move, and scale.

00:13:53.239 --> 00:13:59.679
A mark is a visual element like a dot or a line, a stat defines a statistical operation,

00:13:59.679 --> 00:14:07.000
a move implements a positional adjustment, and a scale maps from data to visual properties.

00:14:07.000 --> 00:14:10.119
Let's see these in action.

00:14:10.119 --> 00:14:14.520
So you call the plot constructor with a data source and some assignments from variables

00:14:14.520 --> 00:14:17.400
in the data set to roles in the plot.

00:14:17.400 --> 00:14:21.640
Now this looks a lot like a function call in the classic interface, but if we compiled

00:14:21.640 --> 00:14:26.559
this spec, we would see just an empty graph with some labels on the axes.

00:14:26.559 --> 00:14:32.679
You won't actually get a data visualization until we add layers to the plot.

00:14:32.679 --> 00:14:37.760
And you do that, hopefully intuitively, with a method called plot.add.

00:14:37.760 --> 00:14:41.520
So every layer is defined by at least a mark object.

00:14:41.520 --> 00:14:47.679
Here I'm using a dot mark, so it's producing a scatter plot.

00:14:47.679 --> 00:14:51.599
And you'll notice that when I define the layer, I'm setting the point size of the dot to a

00:14:51.599 --> 00:14:57.719
specific value, and then also associating the marker, the dot marker, with another column

00:14:57.719 --> 00:15:00.640
from the data frame.

00:15:00.640 --> 00:15:03.440
So there's three ways to define visual properties here.

00:15:03.440 --> 00:15:08.239
There's properties that are in the plot constructor that are mapped in all layers.

00:15:08.239 --> 00:15:14.159
There's properties defined in the mark constructor that are set directly to the value you give,

00:15:14.159 --> 00:15:16.200
independent of any of the data.

00:15:16.200 --> 00:15:24.520
And then properties defined in the call to plot.add, which are mapped, but in a layer-specific way.

00:15:24.520 --> 00:15:28.200
For this plot, there's no real difference between whether you specify color in the plot

00:15:28.200 --> 00:15:34.440
constructor or when you're calling add, but if we added another layer, such as a line

00:15:34.440 --> 00:15:44.440
representing a regression fit, you'd see that only the colors of the line are mapped.

00:15:44.440 --> 00:15:49.880
So as in classic Seaborn, the default scales are chosen for each mapping variable based

00:15:49.880 --> 00:15:54.640
on the data types and other inferences about the plot spec.

00:15:54.640 --> 00:15:59.799
But there's a method called plot.scale that allows you to explicitly override and supply

00:15:59.799 --> 00:16:01.719
the mapping you want to use.

00:16:01.719 --> 00:16:06.559
So for example, here I'm choosing a slightly more intuitive mapping from true-false to

00:16:06.559 --> 00:16:09.159
a circle and an X.

00:16:09.159 --> 00:16:14.400
For full customization, you can pass an instance of a scale object, like a nominal scale or

00:16:14.400 --> 00:16:16.359
a continuous scale.

00:16:16.359 --> 00:16:20.359
There's also a number of shorthands, like just passing a dictionary or a list that imply

00:16:20.359 --> 00:16:25.599
a specific scale type.

00:16:25.599 --> 00:16:29.020
The notion of small multiple plots remains very important to Seaborn.

00:16:29.020 --> 00:16:35.960
Any plot can be distributed across a grid of subplots by calling plot.facet and supplying

00:16:35.960 --> 00:16:41.440
one or two additional columns from your data frame that define the rows and the columns

00:16:41.440 --> 00:16:44.760
in the facet grid.

00:16:44.760 --> 00:16:50.299
And there's also a method called plot.pair, which also produces subplots that look a lot

00:16:50.299 --> 00:16:57.520
like a facet plot, but much like the classic Seaborn pair grid class or pair plot function,

00:16:57.520 --> 00:17:03.119
here we're taking multiple columns from the initial data frame and assigning them to the

00:17:03.799 --> 00:17:06.400
different subplot X or Y axes.

00:17:06.400 --> 00:17:11.199
So this is like faceting, and you could basically reshape your data and also accomplish this

00:17:11.199 --> 00:17:18.719
through a facet operation, but sometimes it's more convenient to skip the reshaping step.

00:17:18.719 --> 00:17:23.439
So unlike in the classic Seaborn interface, you use the same term to either map a property

00:17:23.439 --> 00:17:25.479
based on data or set it directly.

00:17:25.479 --> 00:17:28.040
What matters is where you do it.

00:17:28.040 --> 00:17:30.800
And you can map a much wider range of visual properties.

00:17:30.800 --> 00:17:36.040
So that includes multiple color attributes, the alpha or the opacity of the mark, and

00:17:36.040 --> 00:17:38.680
whether the mark is filled.

00:17:38.680 --> 00:17:43.239
Where appropriate, you can control style properties like the marker shape or the dash pattern

00:17:43.239 --> 00:17:46.800
that's used for a line or the edge of a patch.

00:17:46.800 --> 00:17:50.400
There's a number of size-based properties like the point size of a dot mark, the width

00:17:50.400 --> 00:17:56.359
of the lines or edges of a patch, and the strokes that define line art markers.

00:17:57.359 --> 00:18:01.839
If you have a text mark in your plot, you can also control the font size, alignment,

00:18:01.839 --> 00:18:03.920
and offset from the anchor point.

00:18:03.920 --> 00:18:06.959
Usually you'd set these directly, but it's possible to map them too.

00:18:06.959 --> 00:18:12.180
There's no distinction between mappable and unmappable parameters.

00:18:12.180 --> 00:18:14.520
So I think the ergonomics here are a lot better.

00:18:14.520 --> 00:18:17.760
There's no more keyword redirection across multiple functions.

00:18:17.760 --> 00:18:22.839
If you're in a notebook or an IDE, all the properties supported by plot or by a specific

00:18:22.839 --> 00:18:24.560
mark are just going to tab complete out.

00:18:24.560 --> 00:18:27.920
The documentation is going to be right there.

00:18:27.920 --> 00:18:31.760
If you think back to the discussion about adding a gap parameter to all the functions

00:18:31.760 --> 00:18:35.119
that support dodging, that's no longer relevant here.

00:18:35.119 --> 00:18:36.479
There's just a single object.

00:18:36.479 --> 00:18:37.739
It's called dodge.

00:18:37.739 --> 00:18:42.160
You add it to any plot spec, and the marks in that layer will get dodged.

00:18:42.160 --> 00:18:46.959
And the gap parameter can just be defined there.

00:18:46.959 --> 00:18:48.599
There's only three parameters in this class.

00:18:48.640 --> 00:18:54.599
It's very easy to understand what it can do, and then it composes with any mark.

00:18:54.599 --> 00:18:58.040
So we're not in the situation with strip plot and scatter plot where you have to choose

00:18:58.040 --> 00:19:03.560
between categorical adjustments and mapping additional properties.

00:19:03.560 --> 00:19:09.760
The objects interface lets you combine all of these operations into one plot spec.

00:19:09.760 --> 00:19:15.640
Now with that said, this particular example is maybe a little overstuffed with information.

00:19:15.640 --> 00:19:20.760
The classic interface is opinionated, which is a nice way of saying it limits what you

00:19:20.760 --> 00:19:22.479
can do.

00:19:22.479 --> 00:19:26.660
And so usually that takes you towards doing things that make sense, but sometimes it prevents

00:19:26.660 --> 00:19:31.599
you from doing things that make sense in a specific context.

00:19:31.599 --> 00:19:37.560
So the objects interface will make you make plots that maybe don't make so much sense.

00:19:37.560 --> 00:19:41.079
And that's because there will be some data sets, some contexts where this specific set

00:19:41.079 --> 00:19:44.640
of operations, when you throw them all together, does produce an informative graph.

00:19:44.640 --> 00:19:50.920
And so when I was developing the new interface, one objective I had in mind was make it possible

00:19:50.920 --> 00:19:55.459
to produce graphs that really don't make any sense so that you avoid preventing people

00:19:55.459 --> 00:19:59.640
from making plots that do.

00:19:59.640 --> 00:20:04.319
And I think I call this successful.

00:20:04.319 --> 00:20:10.800
So do you want a jittered bar plot with unfilled bars where the edge width represents an ordinal

00:20:10.800 --> 00:20:13.000
variable?

00:20:13.000 --> 00:20:15.680
I kind of hope you don't.

00:20:15.680 --> 00:20:18.880
But if you did, you can make it with seaborne objects.

00:20:18.880 --> 00:20:24.640
Okay, so final slide, what's the status of this work?

00:20:24.640 --> 00:20:29.160
It's released, but in a kind of experimental state, a few things that are kind of being

00:20:29.160 --> 00:20:32.839
sorted out, but it's usable, I use it every day.

00:20:32.839 --> 00:20:36.880
If you use the classic interface and you like it, and this has you concerned that it's going

00:20:36.880 --> 00:20:41.719
away, it's not, it's not being deprecated, I'm going to continue to support it.

00:20:41.719 --> 00:20:43.719
And with that, thank you.

00:20:43.719 --> 00:20:44.719
Thank you.

00:20:44.719 --> 00:20:52.479
I'm going to ask you one really quick question.

00:20:52.479 --> 00:20:56.560
In which language is the backend code for seaborne.objects written?

00:20:56.560 --> 00:20:59.119
It's all Python, it's all still talking to Matplotlib.

00:20:59.119 --> 00:21:03.520
I have some experiments where you can actually compile it down to JavaScript, and we'll see

00:21:03.520 --> 00:21:04.520
what comes of those.

00:21:04.520 --> 00:21:06.880
But yeah, at the moment it's still all Python.

00:21:06.880 --> 00:21:07.880
Thank you very much.

00:21:07.880 --> 00:21:08.280
Let's thank our speaker again.

00:21:11.719 --> 00:21:12.719
Thank you.

00:21:12.719 --> 00:21:12.719


